  "target_response": {
    "text": "Sleep is likely part of it, but the data can only show the two moved together. Your HRV is 58 ms this morning, about 5.4 ms under your 7-day average HRV of 63.4 ms, and last night you slept 388 minutes — roughly 64 minutes below your weekly average of 452 minutes. Short nights often line up with a lower next-morning HRV, so both dipping at once is the expected pattern rather than a coincidence. It isn't proof of a single cause, though: your resting heart rate is 61 bpm, only a touch over its 7-day average resting heart rate of 60 bpm, which argues against anything deeper going on. Tonight's lever: protect a full night at your normal bedtime, then recheck — if HRV bounces back with the sleep, you have your answer.",
